// docs/spec/en/05-unions-and-packed-layout.md §9.4(2)'s note lists an
// id-expression naming a `constexpr` variable as an accepted bound form,
// and (8)'s own accepted example only shows this for a *global*
// `constexpr` constant. A deliberate, documented current implementation
// boundary (not required or forbidden by the spec text itself, which is
// silent on this exact case): a *local* `constexpr` constant used as a
// later local array's bound, within the *same* function, is not yet
// supported -- the early, non-executing pass that resolves array bounds
// ahead of ordinary statement execution does not bind local values into
// its constant-evaluation frame stack. This test pins down today's exact,
// clean rejection behavior for that specific case (not a crash, and not
// silently accepted) -- the same clean diagnostic an ordinary
// non-constant local produces -- as a known, deliberate scope boundary
// for a possible future extension, not a bug to be worked around here.
int main() {
    constexpr int kLocalSize = 4;
    char buf[kLocalSize];
    buf[0] = 'a';
    return 0;
}
